If you cannot face your opponent and fight, you will NEVER be good at pvp (not counting you go around ganking people with 20% health). Unless, of course, you do group pvp. However, I think many people enjoy pvp for the &quot;personal skill&quot; factor instead of random killing. Of course, I could be dead wrong on this assumption, but I think it's fair to say those who built a reputation on individual skill earns far more respect than group gankers, eh?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Way wrong. class balance can be defined as what the class is capable of in all environments under all sorts of circumstances. The sum of all this types of experience is a description of how powerful a class is. The problem with declaring duels to be THE description of class balance is that situations will occur way way way more often than not that are far and away nothing like a duel especially as multiple parties on both sides and mobs become involved.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Unless you are trying to say that unprepared pvp matters more than prepared pvp when you speak of class balance, you are just playing the devils advocate, and poorly. Is it not the essense of pvp to be prepared against most situations at all times? Is it not the mark of a good pvper to predict the tactics of your opponents and counteract them before they even begin to excecute?<br>
<br>
Under your limited definition, in a grouping aspect of pvp Ranger would be at least as viable as a rogue (ability to run away quickly, to joust, to handle mobs, to heal, to dot while the opponent is worrying about other things, to buff), and according to Lady D's accessment, since rangers sucked in Velius (before luclin) rogues must have sucked as well. Do I need to convince you that a well equipped, and actually SKILLED rogue does not suck in group pvp?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> If you balance classes based on what is in fact only a fraction of pvp, that is 1 on 1 fights in a fair enviroment with no interferance in which both parties are totally prepared then what happens in the majority of fights which don't follow that template? Factors you didn't plan on come into play and your &quot;balance&quot; is fubar and meaningless.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Factors you didn't plan on will ALWAYS come into play, it is illogical and down right ridiculous to expect otherwise. Balance in pvp is a measurement of viability, not being able to handle any and all situations as you seem to suggest.<br>
<br>
The only way to test viability is in a controlled environment, I don't think I need to tell you that it's pointless to test something if many variables are introduced into the system. As I said before, the essense of pvp is to try to be prepared against as many situations as possible. This is mainly something the player must do, it has very little to nothing to do with the class being played.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Take poison as an example. In a duel vs a real pvper whose prepared its not very strong. Just put on some pr gear and slap a pr buff on. In a real fight at least on RZ it's very useful because most don't run around with good pr all the time.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This is a fault of theirs for not preparing against and effective PvP tool, and it is an advantage given to you for capitalizing on that.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Do you balance classes based on poison being useless or good? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Having options is always useful. The difference between a prepared duel and unprepared pvp is the clear advantage isn't purely determined by luck (sneaking up on someone and duelist+BS). It is up to the players to manuver for advantage, to find a crack in one's opponent's defenses, and then capitalize on that. <br>
<br>
Jumping an unprepared person either results in a quick kill, or them fleeing, or very rarely a long and dragged out fight. However, dueling against a prepared person will most certainly always result in a fight of skill and tactics where both sides, assuming equally skilled players, rack their brains to find a way to gain an advantage.<br>
<br>
Unprepared pvp happens far more than duels, I will grant you this, and part of a class' viability depends on being able to survive unprepared pvp. We are talking Rangers here, a hybrid, far more versital than pure melees. Do you honestly believe they as a class sucked during Velius? <p><BR>
